f   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":18,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":28,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":38,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda De Beauchamp was born about 1068, in Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England. She had at least 1 son with Richard FitzTurolf. She died in 1110, in Bodmin, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"about 1068–1110":"umbes 1068–1110","1050–1110":"1050–1110","1084–1136":"1084–1136","1068–1110":"1068–1110","1106":"1106","1136":"1136","1068":"1068","1110":"1110","about 1068":"umbes 1068","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1084":"1084","about 1110":"umbe